{"title_page": "Vuvuzela", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox instrument\n| name=Vuvuzela\n| image=Vuvuzela red.jpg\n| image_capt = A modern plastic Vuvuzela\n| background=brass\n| classification=\nBrass<ref>Educal dictionary [https://educalingo.com/en/dic-en/vuvuzela]</ref><!-- the classification \"brass\" refers to how the sound is made, not the material the instrument is made from. See [[brass instrument]] -->\n* Wind\n* [[Brass instrument|Brass]]\n* [[Aerophone]]\n| hornbostel_sachs=423.121.12\n| hornbostel_sachs_desc=Tubular end-blown trumpet with mouthpiece\n| range=Varies by instrument, typically around B\u266d\n| related=[[Kudu#Use in music|Kudu]], [[bugle]]\n| article=\n}}\n[[File:Vuvuzela-DD.jpg|thumb|A black and yellow striped vuvuzela]]\n{{listen |filename=Vuvuzela single note.ogg |image=[[File:Vuvuzelas1.svg|40px]] |title=Vuvuzela note |description=A standard short {{convert|58|cm|ft|adj=on|1}} vuvuzela plays a single B{{music|flat}} note.}}\n\nThe '''vuvuzela''' {{IPAc-en|v|u\u02d0|v|u\u02d0|\u02c8|z|\u025b|l|\u0259}}, also known as '''lepatata''' (its [[Tswana language|Tswana]] name),{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} is a [[plastic]] [[Horn (acoustic)|horn]], about 65 centimetres (2&nbsp;ft) long, which produces a loud monotone note, typically around [[B\u266d (musical note)|B\u266d]] [[Scientific pitch notation|3]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/10312794.stm|title=10 things about the vuvuzela |work=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 15, 2010}}</ref> (the B\u266d below [[C (musical note)#Middle C|middle C]]).<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/se/30760.html|title=Trumping the trumpets: how audio engineering helps tone down vuvuzela disruption|date=June 18, 2010|publisher=Queen Mary College University of London}}</ref> Some models are made in two parts to facilitate storage, and this design also allows pitch variation. Many types of vuvuzela, made by several manufacturers, may produce various intensity and frequency outputs.<ref name=\"Journal1\">{{Cite journal|format=PDF|title=Vuvuzela sound measurements|url=http://www.samj.org.za/index.php/samj/article/viewFile/4098/2735|journal=South African Medical Journal|volume=100|issue=4|date=April 2010|page=192|first1=De Wet|last1=Swanepoel|first2=James W|last2=Hall III|first3=Dirk|last3=Koekemoer|location=Cape Town, South Africa|doi=10.7196/samj.4098|pmid=20459951}}</ref> The intensity of these outputs depends on the blowing technique and pressure exerted.<ref name=\"Journal1\" />\n\nTraditionally made and inspired from a [[kudu]] horn, the vuvuzela was used to summon distant villagers to attend community gatherings.<ref name=\"Journal2\" />{{Dubious|Disputed information|date=July 2010}} The vuvuzela is commonly used at [[association football|football]] matches in [[South Africa]],<ref name=fifa>{{cite web|url= https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/destination/southafricafromatoz/letter=v/index.html|title=V is for Vuvuzela|work=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|access-date=September 9, 2008}}</ref> and it has become a symbol of South African football as the stadiums are filled with its sound.<ref name=\"Journal2\">{{Cite journal|title=Vuvuzela&nbsp;\u2013 good for your team, bad for your ears|url=http://www.scielo.org.za/pdf/samj/v100n2/v100n2a15.pdf|journal=South African Medical Journal|volume=100|issue=4|date=February 2010|pages=99\u2013100|first1=De Wet|last1=Swanepoel|first2=James W|last2=Hall III|first3=Dirk|last3=Koekemoer|location=Cape Town, South Africa|doi = 10.7196/samj.3697|pmid=20459912}}</ref> The intensity of the sound caught the attention of the global football community during the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in anticipation of South Africa hosting the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"Journal2\" />\n\nThe vuvuzela has been the subject of controversy when used by spectators at football matches. Its high sound pressure levels at close range can lead to permanent [[hearing loss]] for unprotected ears after exposure,<ref name=\"Journal3\">{{Cite journal|url= http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0256-95742010000400024&lng=en&nrm=iso&tlng=en |journal=South African Medical Journal|title=Football match spectator sound exposure and effect on hearing: A pretest-post-test study |first1=D Wet|last1=Swanepoel|first2=James W|last2=Hall III|date=April 2010|volume=100 |issue=4|location=Cape Town, South Africa|pmid= 20459971|pages= 239\u201342|doi=10.7196/samj.4091}}</ref> with a [[Sound intensity#Sound intensity level|sound level]] of 120 [[decibel|dB(A)]] (the threshold of pain) at {{convert|1|m|ft|spell=in}} from the device opening.<ref name=\"Journal2\" />\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:Shona witch doctor (Zimbabwe).jpg|thumb|[[Kudu]] vuvuzela blown by a [[N'anga]] in Zimbabwe in 1989.]]\n[[File:The Dinner Horn (Blowing the Horn at Seaside), by Winslow Homer, 1870.png|left|thumb|The Dinner Horn (Blowing the Horn at Seaside), by [[Winslow Homer]], 1870.]]\nPlastic [[aerophone]]s, like ''corneta'' and similar devices, have been used in [[Brazil]] and other Latin American countries since the 1960s.\n\nThese plastic horns have been marketed and available in the United States as \"Stadium Horns\" since the mid-1960s.<ref>{{Cite episode\n| title = 8th Inning \u2013 A Whole New Ballgame\n| episodelink = \n| url = \n| series = Baseball\n| serieslink = Baseball (TV series)\n| credits = Ken Burns\n| network = PBS\n| station = \n| city = \n| airdate = September 27, 1994\n| began = \n| ended = \n| season = 1\n| seriesno = \n| number = \n| minutes = 82\n| transcript = \n| transcripturl = \n| quote = at 1:22:12, crowd shot of [[Fenway Park]]. In the upper left corner of the frame, two mass-produced type plastic Stadium Horns/Vuvuzelas are clearly visible.}}</ref> Similar horns have been in existence for much longer. An instrument that looks like a vuvuzela appears in [[Winslow Homer|Winslow Homer's]] 1870 woodcut \"The Dinner Horn\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/brooklynmuseum-o2502-the-dinner-horn|publisher=Brooklyn Museum of Art|title=The Dinner Horn}}</ref>\n\nThe origins of the device is disputed. The term ''vuvuvuvuvuvuvuvuvuzela'' was first used in South Africa from the [[Zulu language]] or [[Nguni languages|Nguni]] dialect meaning to make a ''vuvu'' sound (directly translated: vuvu-ing).{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} Controversies over the invention arose in early 2010. South African [[Kaizer Chiefs F.C.|Kaizer Chiefs]] fan Freddie \"Saddam\" <!-- NOT A SPELLING ERROR -->Maake<!-- NOT A SPELLING ERROR --> claimed the invention of the vuvuzela by fabricating an aluminium version in 1965 from a bicycle horn and has photographic evidence of himself holding the aluminium vuvuzela in the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=\"Freddie Saddam Maake\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2010-01-08-vuvuzela-creator-blown-off|work=Mail & Guardian |title=Vuvuzela creator blown off?|first=Phathisani|last=Moyo|date=January 8, 2010|location=South Africa}}</ref> He also claimed to have coined ''vuvuzela'' from the Zulu language for \"welcome\", \"unite\" and \"celebration\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/jul/10/i-invented-the-vuvuzela |title=Experience: I invented the vuvuzela|first=Freddie|last=Maake|date=July 10, 2010|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London}}</ref> Plastics factory Masincedane Sport popularised the ubiquitous plastic vuvuzela commonly heard at South African football games in 2002,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://g.sports.yahoo.com/soccer/world-cup/news/vuvuzela-inventor-cashes-in-on-success-at-wcup--fbintl_ap-wcup-vuvuzela.html|title=Vuvuzela innovator cashes in on success at WCup|first=Raf|last=Casert|date=June 18, 2010|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Inc|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622001244/http://g.sports.yahoo.com/soccer/world-cup/news/vuvuzela-inventor-cashes-in-on-success-at-wcup--fbintl_ap-wcup-vuvuzela.html|archivedate=June 22, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the [[Nazareth Baptist Church]] claimed the vuvuzela belonged to their church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8458829.stm|title=Unholy row over World Cup trumpet|access-date=January 16, 2010 |last=Fisher |first=Jonah |date=January 16, 2010 |work=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==International tournaments==\n[[File:Vuvuzelas 1.jpg|thumb|left|A 2010 [[FIFA World Cup]] crowd blowing vuvuzelas]]\nThe world association football governing body, [[FIFA]], proposed banning vuvuzelas from stadiums, as they were seen as potential weapons for [[Football hooliganism|hooligans]] and could be used in [[ambush marketing]].{{cn|are those really the reasons FIFA claimed?|date=March 2019}} Columnist Jon Qwelane described the device as \"an instrument from hell\".<ref name=\"jqInstrumentFromHell\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/Columnists/Archive/JonQwelane/Ban-the-vuvuzela-20050207|title=Ban the vuvuzela|last=Qwelane|first=Jon|work=News24|publisher=24.com|date=February 7, 2005|location=South Africa}}</ref> South African football authorities argued that the vuvuzela was part of the South African football experience.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Makhaye |first=Chris |date=July 13, 2008|title=Blasts of joy as vuvuzelas unbanned|publisher=IOL|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=6&click_id=2871&art_id=vn20080713120228203C272609}}</ref> The Spanish midfielder [[Xabi Alonso]] said, \"Those trumpets? That noise I don't like&nbsp;... FIFA must ban those things&nbsp;... it is not nice to have a noise like that\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.capeargus.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=5041732|title=Ban the noisy vuvuzela, says Alonso|date=June 18, 2009|work=Cape Argus|publisher= Cape Argus & Independent Online}}</ref> Dutch coach [[Bert van Marwijk]] remarked, \"...&nbsp;it was annoying&nbsp;... in the stadiums you get used to it but it is still unpleasant\".<ref name=\"ESPN Soccernet\">{{Cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=656178&sec=global&cc=5901 |title=Dutch coach joins chorus to ban vuvuzela|work=ESPNsoccernet|publisher=Walt Disney Internet Group|agency=Reuters|date=June 20, 2009 |access-date=June 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCommentator Farayi Mungazi said, \"Banning the vuvuzela would take away the distinctiveness of a South African World Cup ... absolutely essential for an authentic South African footballing experience\".<ref name=\"BBC2\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8108691.stm|title=In defence of the vuvuzela|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 19, 2009|last=Mungazi|first=Farayi|access-date=June 14, 2010}}</ref> FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] responded, \"we should not try to Europeanise an African World Cup ... that is what African and South Africa football is all about \u2013 noise, excitement, dancing, shouting and enjoyment\".<ref name=\"BBC2\" /><ref name=\"ESPN Soccernet\" /> Despite the criticisms, FIFA agreed to permit their use in stadiums during the 2009 FIFA Confederations Cup and 2010 FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Fifa gives Vuvuzelas thumbs up|date=July 11, 2008|url=http://www.news24.com/xArchive/Sport/SWC2010/Fifa-gives-Vuvuzelas-thumbs-up-20080711|agency=South African Press Association|work=News24|publisher=24.com|location=South Africa}}</ref> The South African football authority argued that during FIFA World Cup 2010, vuvuzelas achieved great popularity, though TV spectators suffered a lot due to vuvuzela noise pollution.<ref name=\"ESPN Soccernet\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n===2010 FIFA World Cup===\n====Marketing====\n[[Hyundai Group|Hyundai]] constructed the world's largest working vuvuzela as part of a marketing campaign for the World Cup. The {{convert|35|m|ft|adj=on}} blue vuvuzela mounted on the [[Foreshore Freeway Bridge]], [[Cape Town]] was intended to be used at the beginning of each match; however, it had not yet sounded a note during the World Cup, as its volume was a cause of concern to city authorities.<ref name=\"SilentGiant\">{{Cite news|last=Hudson|first=Alexandra|title=Giant vuvuzela waits for council go-ahead to toot|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idAFJOE65H0MC20100618|access-date=June 19, 2010|agency=Reuters Africa|date=June 18, 2010|publisher=Thomson Reuters Corporate}}</ref>\n\n====Reception====\n{{listen |filename=2010-06-14_VOA_News_report_-_Noisy_Vuvuzelas_Cause_Concern_at_World_Cup.ogg |title=Noisy Vuvuzelas cause concern |image=[[File:Vuvuzelas1.svg|40px]] |description=[[Voice of America]] report on the impact of vuvuzelas at the 2010 FIFA World Cup.}}\nIts ubiquity led to many suggestions for limiting its use, muffling its sound, and even an outright ban.<ref>{{cite web|title=Noisy Vuvuzelas Cause Concern at World Cup|last=Schy|first=Steve|location=Washington, D.C., United States of America|url=http://www1.voanews.com/english/news/africa/Noisy-Vuvuzelas-Cause-Concern-at-World-Cup-96305284.html|work=Voice of America|publisher=Federal Government of the United States|access-date=June 18, 2010|date=June 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Organizers consider silencing vuvuzelas|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/5282269/ce/us/organizers-consider-silencing-vuvuzelas&cc=5901?ver=us|work=ESPNsoccernet|publisher=Walt Disney Internet Group|access-date=June 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBroadcasting organisations experienced difficulties with their presentations. Television and radio audiences often heard only the sound of vuvuzelas.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment_and_arts/10317767.stm|title=BBC receives 545 vuvuzela complaints over World Cup|work=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 15, 2010|access-date=June 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN1\">{{Cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/5287552/ce/us/bbc-mulls-vuvuzela-free-option-viewers?cc=5901&ver=us|title=Host broadcasters to 'filter' noise|date=June 15, 2010|agency=Associated Press|work=ESPNsoccernet|publisher=Walt Disney Internet Group}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=BBC mulls vuvuzela-free option for irked viewers|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/news?slug=txwcupvuvuzelasbbc|access-date=June 17, 2010|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Inc|date=June 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"nyp1\">{{Cite news| title=Buzz off, vuvuzelas! | work=New York Post|publisher=NYP Holdings, Inc| url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/more_sports/buzz_off_vuvuzelas_FPa9BYlmlRWJMsF1W65cyJ?CMP=OTC-rss&FEEDNAME= | first=Elio | last=Valenti | date=June 13, 2010}}</ref> The [[BBC]], [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]], [[ESPN]] and [[Sky UK|BSkyB]] have examined the possibility of filtering the ambient noise while maintaining game commentary.<ref name=\"BBC1\" /><ref name=\"ESPN1\" />\n\nThe vuvuzelas raised health and safety concerns. Competitors believed the incessant noise hampered the ability of the players to get their rest, and degraded the quality of team performance.<ref name=\"bbcponder\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8737455.stm|title=World Cup 2010: Organisers will not ban vuvuzelas|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"google1\">{{Cite news|agency=Agence France-Presse|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5ghUbctrzM88GqP_A_qJZppPbhjVw |title=World Cup organiser mulls vuvuzela ban|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref> Other critics remarked that vuvuzelas disrupted team communication and players' concentration during matches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/article454621.ece |title=It is impossible to communicate, it's like being deaf: Messi|work=The Hindu|agency=Deutsche Presse-Agentur|access-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rnw.nl/international-justice/bulletin/ronaldo-hits-out-vuvuzelas|title=Ronaldo hits out at vuvuzelas|publisher=Radio Nederland Wereldomroep|agency=Netherlands National News, Agence France-Presse|access-date=June 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617160420/http://www.rnw.nl/international-justice/bulletin/ronaldo-hits-out-vuvuzelas|archive-date=June 17, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Demand for earplugs to protect from hearing loss during the World Cup outstripped supply, with many pharmacies out of stock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/Content.aspx?id=111728 |title=Worried fans right to seek ear plugs, says Phonak|work=BusinessDay|publisher=BDFM Publishers|last=Chilwane|first=Luphert|date=June 11, 2010|access-date=June 15, 2010}}</ref> One major vuvuzela manufacturer even began selling its own earplugs to spectators.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/Vuvuzelas-unplugged-for-some-20100611|title=Vuvuzelas unplugged for some|work=Sport24|publisher=24.com|location=South Africa|date=June 11, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722052239/http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/Vuvuzelas-unplugged-for-some-20100611|archivedate=July 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Audio filtration====\n[[Band-stop filter|Notch filtering]], an audio filtration technique, is proposed to reduce the vuvuzela sound in broadcasts and increase clarity of commentary audio. The vuvuzela produces notes at a frequency of approximately 235&nbsp;Hz and its [[overtone|first partial]] at 465&nbsp;Hz.<ref>{{cite web|title=How to Silence Vuvuzela Horns in World Cup Broadcasts|url=http://lifehacker.com/5564085/how-to-silence-vuvuzela-horns-with-an-eq-filter|last=Pash|first=Adam|date=June 15, 2010|publisher=Gawker Media|work=Lifehacker|access-date=June 17, 2010}}</ref> However, this filtration technique affects the clarity of commentary audio. Proposals of [[adaptive filter]]s by universities and research organisations address this issue by preserving the amplitude and clarity of the commentators' voices and crowd noise.<ref name=\"qmvuvupr\">{{Cite press release | title = Trumping the trumpets: how audio engineering helps tone down vuvuzela disruption | publisher = Queen Mary University of London | date = June 18, 2010 |work=Centre for Digital Music| url = http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/se/30760.html | access-date = June 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"vuvux\">{{cite web|url=http://vuvux.com/ |title=Prosoniq VuvuX|publisher=Prosoniq Products Software GmbH|access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stardock.com/labs/devuvuzelator/ |title=The Devuvuzelator|first1=Jeff|last1=Bargmann|last2=University of London|first2=Queen Mary|publisher=Stardock Corporation |access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> Such filtration techniques have been adopted by some cable television providers.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portuguese cable provider offers vuvuzela muting service for World Cup games|url=http://trueslant.com/marceloballve/2010/06/17/portuguese-cable-provider-offers-vuvuzela-muting-service-for-world-cup-games/|date=June 17, 2010|last=Ballve|first=Marcelo|work=True/Slant}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 FIFA World Cup ===\nVuvuzelas made a comeback at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia, used mainly by [[Iran national football team|Iranian supporters]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-2018-morocco-vs-iran-highlights-vuvuzela-goals-five-things-learned-score-a8401226.html|title=Five things we learned as vuvuzelas fail to drown out late Iran goal|date=June 15, 2018|website=The Independent}}</ref> Much like in 2010, there was a backlash against their use.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/vuvuzelas-world-cup-morocco-iran/|title=Vuvuzelas are back at the World Cup and people are fuming|date=June 16, 2018|publisher=inews.co.uk|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/football/vuvuzelas-i-hate-them-but-they-are-back-1.2240135|title=Vuvuzelas: I hate them, but they are back|first=Shyam A. Krishna, Opinion|last=Editor|date=June 21, 2018|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Health effects and regulation==\n===Health concerns===\n[[File:Vuvuzelas Warning.jpg|thumb|right|Some vuvuzelas carry a safety warning graphic.]]\nA study in 2010 by Dr Ruth McNerney of the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] and colleagues, concluded that the spread of diseases by means of vuvuzelas was possible.<ref name=\"MiaSnyman\">{{Cite news|last=Snyman|first=Mia|title=Study: Vuvuzela could spread colds and flu|publisher=Boston.com|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/articles/2010/06/10/study_vuvuzela_could_spread_colds_and_flu/|agency=Associated Press |date=June 10, 2010|access-date=November 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/playbook/2011/05/vuvuzelas-airborne-germs |date=May 24, 2011 |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |author=Brian Mossop |title=Besides Noise, Vuvuzelas May Spread Airborne Germs}}</ref> McNerney found tiny droplets at the bottom of a vuvuzela that can carry [[flu]] and [[Common cold|cold germs]] that are small enough to stay suspended in the air for hours, and can enter into the airways of a person's lungs. The vuvuzelas can infect others on a greater scale than coughing or shouting.\n\nThe vuvuzelas have the potential to cause [[noise-induced hearing loss]].<ref name=\"Journal1\" /><ref name=\"Journal2\" /><ref name=\"Journal3\" /><ref name=\"MiaSnyman\" /> Prof James Hall III, Dr Dirk Koekemoer, De Wet Swanepoel and colleagues at the [[University of Pretoria]] found that vuvuzelas can have a negative effect when a listener's eardrums are exposed to the instrument's high-intensity sound. The vuvuzelas produce an average sound pressure of 113&nbsp;dB(A) at {{convert|2|m|ft|spell=in|0}} from the device opening.<ref name=\"Journal2\" /> The study finds that subjects should not be exposed to more than 15 minutes per day at an intensity of 100&nbsp;dB(A).<ref name=\"Journal2\" /> The study assumes that if a single vuvuzela emits a sound that is dangerously loud to subjects within a {{convert|2|m|ft|spell=in|adj=on|0}} radius, and numerous vuvuzelas are typically blown together for the duration of a match, it may put spectators at a significant risk of hearing loss.<ref name=\"Journal2\" /> Hearing loss experts at the U.S. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) recommend that exposure at the 113&nbsp;dB(A) level not exceed 45 seconds per day.<ref name=NIOSHvuvuzela>{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2010/06/17/vuvuzelas/ |title=CDC/NIOSH Science Blog \u2013 Vuvuzelas: What's the Buzz? June 2010|work=NIOSH|publisher=cdc.com/niosh|date=June 2010}}</ref> A newer model has a modified mouthpiece that reduces the volume by 20&nbsp;dB.<ref name=Sport24>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/New-vuvuzelas-turn-down-volume-20100614|title=New vuvuzelas turn down volume|work=Sport24|publisher=24.com|access-date=June 14, 2010|date=June 14, 2010|location=South Africa|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222134753/http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/New-vuvuzelas-turn-down-volume-20100614|archivedate=February 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Noise levels and bans===\nConcerns about the constant intensities produced by the vuvuzelas during the 2010 FIFA World Cup matches were raised independently by representatives of international football teams, spectators and sports commentators. The noise levels that were demonstrated during the 2010 FIFA World Cup prompted various sporting organisations to ban the vuvuzela at future events and venues, even including future World Cups:\n\n* [[Wembley Stadium]] (as part of an overall ban of noisemakers)<ref name=\"WembleynBan\">{{Cite web |title=Rules & Regulations |work=Wembley Stadium |url=http://www.wembleystadium.com/TheStadium/StadiumGuide/RulesnRegulations|access-date=June 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/06/wooomp-fifa-bans-vuvuzelas-from-brazilian-world-cup/372195/|title=Wooomp: FIFA Bans Vuvuzelas from Brazilian World Cup|first=Connor|last=Simpson|date=June 4, 2014|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/2018-world-cup/88426/2018-world-cup-roll-up-for-obese-person-tickets|title=2018 World Cup: Roll up for 'obese person' tickets|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s\n* All sporting events at the [[Cardiff City Stadium|Cardiff City]], [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]], and [[Millennium Stadium]]s<ref>{{Cite news|title=Sports fans in Cardiff spared vuvuzela|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/south_east_wales/10353020.stm|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 18, 2010|access-date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]<ref name=\"WimbledonBan\">{{Cite news|last=Summers|first=Chris|title=Wimbledon crackdown on vuvuzelas |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tennis/wimbledon/8744027.stm|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=June 19, 2010 | date=June 16, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Lord's|Lord's Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/call-to-ban-vuvuzelas-at-edgbaston-127870|title=Call to ban vuvuzelas at Edgbaston|first=Neil|last=Elkes|date=July 9, 2010|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Vuvu gets big no-no from AFL|last=Doherty|first=Elissa|newspaper=Herald Sun|publisher=News Corporation|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/vuvu-gets-big-no-no-from-afl/story-e6frf9if-1225880671282|date=June 17, 2010|access-date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* The [[WACA Ground]] in Perth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waca.com.au/ground/at-the-ground/ground-entry-conditions|title=Ground Entry Conditions&nbsp;\u2014 WACA Western Australia Cricket Association|website=www.waca.com.au|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[The Gabba]] Cricket Ground in Brisbane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/the-ashes-2017-barmy-armys-new-chants-revealed-before-gabba-test/news-story/217258319be9b13bc92cd43d70ef06aa|title=Chant like England's Barmy Army|date=November 23, 2017|website=www.couriermail.com.au}}</ref>\n* The [[Sydney Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketnsw.com.au/news/attending-the-odi-between-australia-and-india-at-the-scg/2012-02-24|title=Attending the ODI between Australia and India at the SCG|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* The now defunct [[Champions League Twenty20]] cricket tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/sep/08/county-cricket-live|title=County cricket&nbsp;\u2014 as it happened!&nbsp;\u2014 Andy Wilson, Rob Smyth and Vic Marks|first1=Vic|last1=Marks|first2=Andy|last2=Wilson|first3=Rob|last3=Smyth|date=September 8, 2010|website=the Guardian|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Yankee Stadium]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Vuvuzelas BANNED From Yankee Stadium |work=The Huffington Post|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/06/17/vuvuzelas-banned-from-yan_n_616282.html|date=June 17, 2010|access-date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Fuji Rock Festival]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fujirockfestival.com/news/?id=969|title=\u30d6\u30d6\u30bc\u30e9\u306e\u6301\u3061\u8fbc\u307f\u53ca\u3073\u4f7f\u7528\u7981\u6b62\u306e\u304a\u9858\u3044|work=FujiRockFestival.com|publisher=SMASH Corporation|date=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n* The [[Southeastern Conference]] of US college sports<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/sec-leave-your-vuvuzelas-557799.html|author=Kristi E. Swartz|title=SEC: leave your vuvuzelas at home|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=2010-07-05}}</ref>\n* [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] events.<ref>{{Cite news|title=No Vuvuzelas allowed at UFC card|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/extra/mma/news/story?id=5343197|publisher=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=June 30, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] events<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0618/1224272793785.html |title=GAA bans vuvuzelas before they blow away the Croke Park atmosphere \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Fri, Jun 18, 2010 |work=The Irish Times |date=June 18, 2010 |access-date=2010-09-14}}</ref>\n* [[Little League World Series]] (from 2010 onward)\n* [[Providence Park]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pgepark.com/guest-guide |title=Guest Guide |publisher=Portland Timbers |access-date=2011-03-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110127134957/http://www.pgepark.com/guest-guide |archive-date=January 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[UEFA]], including all [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]], and [[European Championship]] matches<ref>[http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/5518726/uefa-bans-vuvuzelas-euro-2012-champions-league UEFA Enacts Vuvuzelas Ban], ''ESPN.com'', September 1, 2010</ref>\n* [[Rugby World Cup]] (starting in [[2011 Rugby World Cup|2011]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sarugby.com/news/News/article/sid=13830.html|title=No vuvuzelas at RWC 2011|work=SARugby.com|publisher=SARugby.com|date=June 29, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703061050/http://www.sarugby.com/news/News/article/sid%3D13830.html|archivedate=July 3, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Kontinental Hockey League]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khl.ru/news/2010/7/23/27717.html |script-title=ru:\u041a\u0425\u041b \u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0443\u0432\u0443\u0437\u0435\u043b |date=July 23, 2010 |publisher=[[Kontinental Hockey League]] |access-date=July 23, 2010 |language=Russian}}</ref>\n* [[2010 FIBA World Championship]] and other basketball tournaments from then on<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportas.delfi.lt/eurobasket2003/pasaulio-krepsinio-cempionate-vuvuzelu-negirdesime.d?id=35095573 |title=Pasaulio krep\u0161inio \u010dempionate vuvuzel\u0173 negird\u0117sime \u2013 DELFI \u017dinios |publisher=Sportas.delfi.lt |access-date=2010-09-14}}</ref>\n* [[National Football League]] (as part of an overall ban of noisemakers)\n* [[Evolution Championship Series|The Evolution Championship Series]] for [[Fighting game|fighting]] [[Esports|games]].\n* [[Vermont Principals' Association]] [[Amateur sports#High school sports|High school sports]]\n*\u00d6FB Bundesliga\n*Bundesliga (in some stadiums)\n\n[[File:Sneijder Heitinga.jpg|thumb|left|[[Wesley Sneijder]] blowing on a vuvuzela]]\nSome shopping centres in South Africa banned the use of vuvuzelas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ewn.co.za/articleprog.aspx?id=41683|title=No vuvuzelas inside Sandton City|work=Eyewitness News|publisher=Primedia Broadcasting|last=Child|first=Katharine|date=June 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006054626/http://www.ewn.co.za/articleprog.aspx?id=41683|archivedate=October 6, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=vn20100616043817493C787065|title=Shopping mall silences vuvuzela|date=June 16, 2010|work=IOL|last=Dardagan|first=Colleen|agency=South African Press Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/sport/soccer/article.aspx?id=410355|title=Vuvuzelas get red card in malls|publisher=Avusa Media Limited|work=Daily Dispatch Online|first=Msindisi|last=Fengu|date=June 18, 2010}}</ref> They were also banned at the 2010 [[Baltimore]] [[anime convention]] [[Otakon]].<ref name=\"Otakon\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.otakon.com/news_article.asp?id=539|title=Vuvuzela ban in effect|first=Arruda|last=Lou|date=July 11, 2010|work=Otakon.com}}</ref>  The convention committee declared that any attendee carrying a vuvuzela could have it confiscated from them, and that anyone blowing one could face expulsion from the event.<ref name=\"Otakon\" /><ref name=\"ANNOta\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2010-07-14/no-vuvuzelas-at-otakon|title=No Vuvuzelas at Otakon|date=July 14, 2010|work=Anime News Network}}</ref>\n\nAnother such action was taken in response to the prevalence of the vuvuzelas at the 2010 [[Anime Expo]] based in Los Angeles, attended by representatives of Otakon who felt the disruption led to discomfort for some of the attendees of Anime Expo which they wished to avoid at the later Baltimore event.<ref name=\"ANNOta\" />\n\nNine English [[Premier League]] clubs have banned the device. Five clubs ([[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/vuvuzelas-not-welcome- |title=Vuvuzelas not welcome at Emirates Stadium! |publisher=Arsenal.com |date=July 20, 2010 |access-date=2010-09-14}}</ref> [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]) have banned them due to health and safety reasons while [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] have barred them because of policy against musical instruments. [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] banned vuvuzelas from [[Old Trafford]] on August 13, 2010. However, two clubs ([[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]) have allowed them. {{citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nThe organisers of the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympic Games]] placed a ban on vuvuzelas at the sporting event.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/no-frisbees-picnic-hampers-or-vuvuzelas-items-banned-from-the-london-2012-olympics-7936428.html |title= No frisbees, picnic hampers or vuvuzelas: items banned from the London 2012 Olympics |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= July 12, 2012 |publisher=BBC News |access-date= August 30, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Usage in protests==\nOn July 13, 2010, protesters with vuvuzelas converged on [[BP]]'s London headquarters to protest the company's handling of the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]].<ref>{{Cite news | author = CNN Wire Staff | title = Vuvuzela protest planned at BP HQ | work = CNN.com Breaking News | publisher = CNN | date = July 13, 2010 | url = http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/07/13/uk.bp.vuvuzela.protest/}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Wisconsin]], anti-[[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], pro-union [[2011 Wisconsin protests|2011 Wisconsin protesters]] have made use of vuvuzelas. A Madison DJ, Nick Nice, [http://www.thedailypage.com/isthmus/article.php?article=33472 ordered 200] and distributed them to his fellow protesters. The Madison police even issued permits for use of the vuvuzelas ''inside'' the capitol.{{Citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\nIn March 2012, German protesters used vuvuzelas during the official traditional torchlight ceremony, the [[Gro\u00dfer Zapfenstreich]], which bid farewell to [[President of Germany]] [[Christian Wulff]]. Wulff had resigned earlier over corruption allegations, yet he still received the honor of the military ceremony, which left Germany divided. [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0,1518,820452,00.html Tr\u00f6ten beim Zapfenstreich: Bellevue beschwert sich \u00fcber Vuvuzela-Demo]\n\n== Usage in music ==\nUsage of vuvuzela in art music is limited. One of the few compositions made for it is a baroque-style [[double concerto]] in C major for vuvuzela, [[organ (music)|organ]] (or [[harpsichord]]) and string orchestra, written by [[Timo Kiiskinen]], Professor of Church Music in [[Sibelius Academy]], [[Helsinki]]; organ version of this concerto was premiered on 21 October 2010 at the Organ Hall of Sibelius Academy, and harpsichord version on 19 December 2010 at Pro Puu gallery in Lahti.<ref>https://cris.uniarts.fi/crisyp/disp/_/fi/cr_redir_all/fet/fet/sea?direction=2&id=3477372 (in Finnish)</ref><ref>\"Barokkiyhtyeen joulukonsertissa soi vuvuzela\" [http://www.ess.fi/uutiset/kulttuurijaviihde/2010/12/16/barokkiyhtyeen-joulukonsertissa-soi-vuvuzela]. ''Etel\u00e4-Suomen sanomat'' 16.12.2010 (in Finnish)</ref>\n\nAlternative rock band Catzo Music All-Stars used two vuvuzelas as the basis of its 2010 song \"Larissa Riquelme (reprise)\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Makarapa]]&nbsp;\u2014 hand-made hats worn by spectators to show their team support\n* [[Air horn#Portable or personal air horns|Portable or personal air horns]]&nbsp;\u2014 produce sounds similar to the vuvuzela\n* [[Ratchet (instrument)|Football rattle]]&nbsp;\u2014 a percussion instrument which produces a clicking and rattling noise\n* [[Thundersticks]]&nbsp;\u2014 narrow plastic balloons used as promotional noise makers\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Vuvuzelas}}\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/africa/10312794.stm 10 Things about the Vuvuzela by the BBC]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7X3fkvhd-5g Promotional film for World Cup Mexico 86 \u2013 Mexican plastic trumpets are shown] \u2013 YouTube\n* [http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/64381,in-pictures,news-in-pictures,vuvuzela-day-in-pictures-bafana-world-cup-football-south-africa Vuvuzela Day] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[The First Post]]''\n* {{cite web|last=Moriarty|first=Philip|title=Vuvuzela|url=http://www.sixtysymbols.com/videos/vuvuzela.htm|work=Sixty Symbols|publisher=[[Brady Haran]] for the [[University of Nottingham]]|year=2010}}\n\n{{2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Fanatism in Association football}}\n{{Natural horns and trumpets}}\n\n[[Category:Association football culture]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup controversies]]\n[[Category:Brass instruments]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:Zulu words and phrases]]\n[[Category:South African English]]\n[[Category:Natural horns and trumpets]]\n[[Category:1965 musical instruments]]\n[[Category:2010 controversies]]\n[[Category:South African inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox instrument\n| name=Vuvuzela\n| image=Vuvuzela red.jpg\n| image_capt = A modern plastic Vuvuzela\n| background=brass\n| classification=\nBrass<ref>Educal dictionary [https://educalingo.com/en/dic-en/vuvuzela]</ref><!-- the classification \"brass\" refers to how the sound is made, not the material the instrument is made from. See [[brass instrument]] -->\n* Wind\n* [[Brass instrument|Brass]]\n* [[Aerophone]]\n| hornbostel_sachs=423.121.12\n| hornbostel_sachs_desc=Tubular end-blown trumpet with mouthpiece\n| range=Varies by instrument, typically around B\u266d\n| related=[[Kudu#Use in music|Kudu]], [[bugle]]\n| article=\n}}\n[[File:Vuvuzela-DD.jpg|thumb|A black and yellow striped vuvuzela]]\n{{listen |filename=Vuvuzela single note.ogg |image=[[File:Vuvuzelas1.svg|40px]] |title=Vuvuzela note |description=A standard short {{convert|58|cm|ft|adj=on|1}} vuvuzela plays a single B{{music|flat}} note.}}\n\nThe '''vuvuzela''' {{IPAc-en|v|u\u02d0|v|u\u02d0|\u02c8|z|\u025b|l|\u0259}}, also known as '''lepatata''' (its [[Tswana language|Tswana]] name),{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} is a [[plastic]] [[Horn (acoustic)|horn]], about 65 centimetres (2&nbsp;ft) long, which produces a loud monotone note, typically around [[B\u266d (musical note)|B\u266d]] [[Scientific pitch notation|3]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/10312794.stm|title=10 things about the vuvuzela |work=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 15, 2010}}</ref> (the B\u266d below [[C (musical note)#Middle C|middle C]]).<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/se/30760.html|title=Trumping the trumpets: how audio engineering helps tone down vuvuzela disruption|date=June 18, 2010|publisher=Queen Mary College University of London}}</ref> Some models are made in two parts to facilitate storage, and this design also allows pitch variation. Many types of vuvuzela, made by several manufacturers, may produce various intensity and frequency outputs.<ref name=\"Journal1\">{{Cite journal|format=PDF|title=Vuvuzela sound measurements|url=http://www.samj.org.za/index.php/samj/article/viewFile/4098/2735|journal=South African Medical Journal|volume=100|issue=4|date=April 2010|page=192|first1=De Wet|last1=Swanepoel|first2=James W|last2=Hall III|first3=Dirk|last3=Koekemoer|location=Cape Town, South Africa|doi=10.7196/samj.4098|pmid=20459951}}</ref> The intensity of these outputs depends on the blowing technique and pressure exerted.<ref name=\"Journal1\" />\n\nTraditionally made and inspired from a [[kudu]] horn, the vuvuzela was used to summon distant villagers to attend community gatherings.<ref name=\"Journal2\" />{{Dubious|Disputed information|date=July 2010}} The vuvuzela is commonly used at [[association football|football]] matches in [[South Africa]],<ref name=fifa>{{cite web|url= https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/destination/southafricafromatoz/letter=v/index.html|title=V is for Vuvuzela|work=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association|access-date=September 9, 2008}}</ref> and it has become a symbol of South African football as the stadiums are filled with its sound.<ref name=\"Journal2\">{{Cite journal|title=Vuvuzela&nbsp;\u2013 good for your team, bad for your ears|url=http://www.scielo.org.za/pdf/samj/v100n2/v100n2a15.pdf|journal=South African Medical Journal|volume=100|issue=4|date=February 2010|pages=99\u2013100|first1=De Wet|last1=Swanepoel|first2=James W|last2=Hall III|first3=Dirk|last3=Koekemoer|location=Cape Town, South Africa|doi = 10.7196/samj.3697|pmid=20459912}}</ref> The intensity of the sound caught the attention of the global football community during the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in anticipation of South Africa hosting the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"Journal2\" />\n\nThe vuvuzela has been the subject of controversy when used by spectators at football matches. Its high sound pressure levels at close range can lead to permanent [[hearing loss]] for unprotected ears after exposure,<ref name=\"Journal3\">{{Cite journal|url= http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0256-95742010000400024&lng=en&nrm=iso&tlng=en |journal=South African Medical Journal|title=Football match spectator sound exposure and effect on hearing: A pretest-post-test study |first1=D Wet|last1=Swanepoel|first2=James W|last2=Hall III|date=April 2010|volume=100 |issue=4|location=Cape Town, South Africa|pmid= 20459971|pages= 239\u201342|doi=10.7196/samj.4091}}</ref> with a [[Sound intensity#Sound intensity level|sound level]] of 120 [[decibel|dB(A)]] (the threshold of pain) at {{convert|1|m|ft|spell=in}} from the device opening.<ref name=\"Journal2\" />\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:Shona witch doctor (Zimbabwe).jpg|thumb|[[Kudu]] vuvuzela blown by a [[N'anga]] in Zimbabwe in 1989.]]\n[[File:The Dinner Horn (Blowing the Horn at Seaside), by Winslow Homer, 1870.png|left|thumb|The Dinner Horn (Blowing the Horn at Seaside), by [[Winslow Homer]], 1870.]]\nPlastic [[aerophone]]s, like ''corneta'' and similar devices, have been used in [[Brazil]] and other Latin American countries since the 1960s.\n\nThese plastic horns have been marketed and available in the United States as \"Stadium Horns\" since the mid-1960s.<ref>{{Cite episode\n| title = 8th Inning \u2013 A Whole New Ballgame\n| episodelink = \n| url = \n| series = Baseball\n| serieslink = Baseball (TV series)\n| credits = Ken Burns\n| network = PBS\n| station = \n| city = \n| airdate = September 27, 1994\n| began = \n| ended = \n| season = 1\n| seriesno = \n| number = \n| minutes = 82\n| transcript = \n| transcripturl = \n| quote = at 1:22:12, crowd shot of [[Fenway Park]]. In the upper left corner of the frame, two mass-produced type plastic Stadium Horns/Vuvuzelas are clearly visible.}}</ref> Similar horns have been in existence for much longer. An instrument that looks like a vuvuzela appears in [[Winslow Homer|Winslow Homer's]] 1870 woodcut \"The Dinner Horn\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/brooklynmuseum-o2502-the-dinner-horn|publisher=Brooklyn Museum of Art|title=The Dinner Horn}}</ref>\n\nThe origin of the device is disputed. The term ''vuvuzela'' was first used in South Africa from the [[Zulu language]] or [[Nguni languages|Nguni]] dialect meaning to make a ''vuvu'' sound (directly translated: vuvu-ing).{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} Controversies over the invention arose in early 2010. South African [[Kaizer Chiefs F.C.|Kaizer Chiefs]] fan Freddie \"Saddam\" <!-- NOT A SPELLING ERROR -->Maake<!-- NOT A SPELLING ERROR --> claimed the invention of the vuvuzela by fabricating an aluminium version in 1965 from a bicycle horn and has photographic evidence of himself holding the aluminium vuvuzela in the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=\"Freddie Saddam Maake\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2010-01-08-vuvuzela-creator-blown-off|work=Mail & Guardian |title=Vuvuzela creator blown off?|first=Phathisani|last=Moyo|date=January 8, 2010|location=South Africa}}</ref> He also claimed to have coined ''vuvuzela'' from the Zulu language for \"welcome\", \"unite\" and \"celebration\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/jul/10/i-invented-the-vuvuzela |title=Experience: I invented the vuvuzela|first=Freddie|last=Maake|date=July 10, 2010|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London}}</ref> Plastics factory Masincedane Sport popularised the ubiquitous plastic vuvuzela commonly heard at South African football games in 2002,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://g.sports.yahoo.com/soccer/world-cup/news/vuvuzela-inventor-cashes-in-on-success-at-wcup--fbintl_ap-wcup-vuvuzela.html|title=Vuvuzela innovator cashes in on success at WCup|first=Raf|last=Casert|date=June 18, 2010|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Inc|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622001244/http://g.sports.yahoo.com/soccer/world-cup/news/vuvuzela-inventor-cashes-in-on-success-at-wcup--fbintl_ap-wcup-vuvuzela.html|archivedate=June 22, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the [[Nazareth Baptist Church]] claimed the vuvuzela belonged to their church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8458829.stm|title=Unholy row over World Cup trumpet|access-date=January 16, 2010 |last=Fisher |first=Jonah |date=January 16, 2010 |work=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==International tournaments==\n[[File:Vuvuzelas 1.jpg|thumb|left|A 2010 [[FIFA World Cup]] crowd blowing vuvuzelas]]\nThe world association football governing body, [[FIFA]], proposed banning vuvuzelas from stadiums, as they were seen as potential weapons for [[Football hooliganism|hooligans]] and could be used in [[ambush marketing]].{{cn|are those really the reasons FIFA claimed?|date=March 2019}} Columnist Jon Qwelane described the device as \"an instrument from hell\".<ref name=\"jqInstrumentFromHell\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/Columnists/Archive/JonQwelane/Ban-the-vuvuzela-20050207|title=Ban the vuvuzela|last=Qwelane|first=Jon|work=News24|publisher=24.com|date=February 7, 2005|location=South Africa}}</ref> South African football authorities argued that the vuvuzela was part of the South African football experience.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Makhaye |first=Chris |date=July 13, 2008|title=Blasts of joy as vuvuzelas unbanned|publisher=IOL|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=6&click_id=2871&art_id=vn20080713120228203C272609}}</ref> The Spanish midfielder [[Xabi Alonso]] said, \"Those trumpets? That noise I don't like&nbsp;... FIFA must ban those things&nbsp;... it is not nice to have a noise like that\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.capeargus.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=5041732|title=Ban the noisy vuvuzela, says Alonso|date=June 18, 2009|work=Cape Argus|publisher= Cape Argus & Independent Online}}</ref> Dutch coach [[Bert van Marwijk]] remarked, \"...&nbsp;it was annoying&nbsp;... in the stadiums you get used to it but it is still unpleasant\".<ref name=\"ESPN Soccernet\">{{Cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=656178&sec=global&cc=5901 |title=Dutch coach joins chorus to ban vuvuzela|work=ESPNsoccernet|publisher=Walt Disney Internet Group|agency=Reuters|date=June 20, 2009 |access-date=June 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCommentator Farayi Mungazi said, \"Banning the vuvuzela would take away the distinctiveness of a South African World Cup ... absolutely essential for an authentic South African footballing experience\".<ref name=\"BBC2\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8108691.stm|title=In defence of the vuvuzela|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 19, 2009|last=Mungazi|first=Farayi|access-date=June 14, 2010}}</ref> FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] responded, \"we should not try to Europeanise an African World Cup ... that is what African and South Africa football is all about \u2013 noise, excitement, dancing, shouting and enjoyment\".<ref name=\"BBC2\" /><ref name=\"ESPN Soccernet\" /> Despite the criticisms, FIFA agreed to permit their use in stadiums during the 2009 FIFA Confederations Cup and 2010 FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Fifa gives Vuvuzelas thumbs up|date=July 11, 2008|url=http://www.news24.com/xArchive/Sport/SWC2010/Fifa-gives-Vuvuzelas-thumbs-up-20080711|agency=South African Press Association|work=News24|publisher=24.com|location=South Africa}}</ref> The South African football authority argued that during FIFA World Cup 2010, vuvuzelas achieved great popularity, though TV spectators suffered a lot due to vuvuzela noise pollution.<ref name=\"ESPN Soccernet\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n===2010 FIFA World Cup===\n====Marketing====\n[[Hyundai Group|Hyundai]] constructed the world's largest working vuvuzela as part of a marketing campaign for the World Cup. The {{convert|35|m|ft|adj=on}} blue vuvuzela mounted on the [[Foreshore Freeway Bridge]], [[Cape Town]] was intended to be used at the beginning of each match; however, it had not yet sounded a note during the World Cup, as its volume was a cause of concern to city authorities.<ref name=\"SilentGiant\">{{Cite news|last=Hudson|first=Alexandra|title=Giant vuvuzela waits for council go-ahead to toot|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idAFJOE65H0MC20100618|access-date=June 19, 2010|agency=Reuters Africa|date=June 18, 2010|publisher=Thomson Reuters Corporate}}</ref>\n\n====Reception====\n{{listen |filename=2010-06-14_VOA_News_report_-_Noisy_Vuvuzelas_Cause_Concern_at_World_Cup.ogg |title=Noisy Vuvuzelas cause concern |image=[[File:Vuvuzelas1.svg|40px]] |description=[[Voice of America]] report on the impact of vuvuzelas at the 2010 FIFA World Cup.}}\nIts ubiquity led to many suggestions for limiting its use, muffling its sound, and even an outright ban.<ref>{{cite web|title=Noisy Vuvuzelas Cause Concern at World Cup|last=Schy|first=Steve|location=Washington, D.C., United States of America|url=http://www1.voanews.com/english/news/africa/Noisy-Vuvuzelas-Cause-Concern-at-World-Cup-96305284.html|work=Voice of America|publisher=Federal Government of the United States|access-date=June 18, 2010|date=June 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Organizers consider silencing vuvuzelas|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/5282269/ce/us/organizers-consider-silencing-vuvuzelas&cc=5901?ver=us|work=ESPNsoccernet|publisher=Walt Disney Internet Group|access-date=June 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBroadcasting organisations experienced difficulties with their presentations. Television and radio audiences often heard only the sound of vuvuzelas.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment_and_arts/10317767.stm|title=BBC receives 545 vuvuzela complaints over World Cup|work=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 15, 2010|access-date=June 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN1\">{{Cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/5287552/ce/us/bbc-mulls-vuvuzela-free-option-viewers?cc=5901&ver=us|title=Host broadcasters to 'filter' noise|date=June 15, 2010|agency=Associated Press|work=ESPNsoccernet|publisher=Walt Disney Internet Group}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=BBC mulls vuvuzela-free option for irked viewers|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/news?slug=txwcupvuvuzelasbbc|access-date=June 17, 2010|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Yahoo! Inc|date=June 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"nyp1\">{{Cite news| title=Buzz off, vuvuzelas! | work=New York Post|publisher=NYP Holdings, Inc| url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/more_sports/buzz_off_vuvuzelas_FPa9BYlmlRWJMsF1W65cyJ?CMP=OTC-rss&FEEDNAME= | first=Elio | last=Valenti | date=June 13, 2010}}</ref> The [[BBC]], [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]], [[ESPN]] and [[Sky UK|BSkyB]] have examined the possibility of filtering the ambient noise while maintaining game commentary.<ref name=\"BBC1\" /><ref name=\"ESPN1\" />\n\nThe vuvuzelas raised health and safety concerns. Competitors believed the incessant noise hampered the ability of the players to get their rest, and degraded the quality of team performance.<ref name=\"bbcponder\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8737455.stm|title=World Cup 2010: Organisers will not ban vuvuzelas|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"google1\">{{Cite news|agency=Agence France-Presse|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5ghUbctrzM88GqP_A_qJZppPbhjVw |title=World Cup organiser mulls vuvuzela ban|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref> Other critics remarked that vuvuzelas disrupted team communication and players' concentration during matches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/article454621.ece |title=It is impossible to communicate, it's like being deaf: Messi|work=The Hindu|agency=Deutsche Presse-Agentur|access-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rnw.nl/international-justice/bulletin/ronaldo-hits-out-vuvuzelas|title=Ronaldo hits out at vuvuzelas|publisher=Radio Nederland Wereldomroep|agency=Netherlands National News, Agence France-Presse|access-date=June 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617160420/http://www.rnw.nl/international-justice/bulletin/ronaldo-hits-out-vuvuzelas|archive-date=June 17, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Demand for earplugs to protect from hearing loss during the World Cup outstripped supply, with many pharmacies out of stock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/Content.aspx?id=111728 |title=Worried fans right to seek ear plugs, says Phonak|work=BusinessDay|publisher=BDFM Publishers|last=Chilwane|first=Luphert|date=June 11, 2010|access-date=June 15, 2010}}</ref> One major vuvuzela manufacturer even began selling its own earplugs to spectators.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/Vuvuzelas-unplugged-for-some-20100611|title=Vuvuzelas unplugged for some|work=Sport24|publisher=24.com|location=South Africa|date=June 11, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722052239/http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/Vuvuzelas-unplugged-for-some-20100611|archivedate=July 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Audio filtration====\n[[Band-stop filter|Notch filtering]], an audio filtration technique, is proposed to reduce the vuvuzela sound in broadcasts and increase clarity of commentary audio. The vuvuzela produces notes at a frequency of approximately 235&nbsp;Hz and its [[overtone|first partial]] at 465&nbsp;Hz.<ref>{{cite web|title=How to Silence Vuvuzela Horns in World Cup Broadcasts|url=http://lifehacker.com/5564085/how-to-silence-vuvuzela-horns-with-an-eq-filter|last=Pash|first=Adam|date=June 15, 2010|publisher=Gawker Media|work=Lifehacker|access-date=June 17, 2010}}</ref> However, this filtration technique affects the clarity of commentary audio. Proposals of [[adaptive filter]]s by universities and research organisations address this issue by preserving the amplitude and clarity of the commentators' voices and crowd noise.<ref name=\"qmvuvupr\">{{Cite press release | title = Trumping the trumpets: how audio engineering helps tone down vuvuzela disruption | publisher = Queen Mary University of London | date = June 18, 2010 |work=Centre for Digital Music| url = http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/se/30760.html | access-date = June 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"vuvux\">{{cite web|url=http://vuvux.com/ |title=Prosoniq VuvuX|publisher=Prosoniq Products Software GmbH|access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stardock.com/labs/devuvuzelator/ |title=The Devuvuzelator|first1=Jeff|last1=Bargmann|last2=University of London|first2=Queen Mary|publisher=Stardock Corporation |access-date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> Such filtration techniques have been adopted by some cable television providers.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portuguese cable provider offers vuvuzela muting service for World Cup games|url=http://trueslant.com/marceloballve/2010/06/17/portuguese-cable-provider-offers-vuvuzela-muting-service-for-world-cup-games/|date=June 17, 2010|last=Ballve|first=Marcelo|work=True/Slant}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 FIFA World Cup ===\nVuvuzelas made a comeback at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia, used mainly by [[Iran national football team|Iranian supporters]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-2018-morocco-vs-iran-highlights-vuvuzela-goals-five-things-learned-score-a8401226.html|title=Five things we learned as vuvuzelas fail to drown out late Iran goal|date=June 15, 2018|website=The Independent}}</ref> Much like in 2010, there was a backlash against their use.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/vuvuzelas-world-cup-morocco-iran/|title=Vuvuzelas are back at the World Cup and people are fuming|date=June 16, 2018|publisher=inews.co.uk|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/football/vuvuzelas-i-hate-them-but-they-are-back-1.2240135|title=Vuvuzelas: I hate them, but they are back|first=Shyam A. Krishna, Opinion|last=Editor|date=June 21, 2018|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Health effects and regulation==\n===Health concerns===\n[[File:Vuvuzelas Warning.jpg|thumb|right|Some vuvuzelas carry a safety warning graphic.]]\nA study in 2010 by Dr Ruth McNerney of the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] and colleagues, concluded that the spread of diseases by means of vuvuzelas was possible.<ref name=\"MiaSnyman\">{{Cite news|last=Snyman|first=Mia|title=Study: Vuvuzela could spread colds and flu|publisher=Boston.com|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/articles/2010/06/10/study_vuvuzela_could_spread_colds_and_flu/|agency=Associated Press |date=June 10, 2010|access-date=November 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/playbook/2011/05/vuvuzelas-airborne-germs |date=May 24, 2011 |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |author=Brian Mossop |title=Besides Noise, Vuvuzelas May Spread Airborne Germs}}</ref> McNerney found tiny droplets at the bottom of a vuvuzela that can carry [[flu]] and [[Common cold|cold germs]] that are small enough to stay suspended in the air for hours, and can enter into the airways of a person's lungs. The vuvuzelas can infect others on a greater scale than coughing or shouting.\n\nThe vuvuzelas have the potential to cause [[noise-induced hearing loss]].<ref name=\"Journal1\" /><ref name=\"Journal2\" /><ref name=\"Journal3\" /><ref name=\"MiaSnyman\" /> Prof James Hall III, Dr Dirk Koekemoer, De Wet Swanepoel and colleagues at the [[University of Pretoria]] found that vuvuzelas can have a negative effect when a listener's eardrums are exposed to the instrument's high-intensity sound. The vuvuzelas produce an average sound pressure of 113&nbsp;dB(A) at {{convert|2|m|ft|spell=in|0}} from the device opening.<ref name=\"Journal2\" /> The study finds that subjects should not be exposed to more than 15 minutes per day at an intensity of 100&nbsp;dB(A).<ref name=\"Journal2\" /> The study assumes that if a single vuvuzela emits a sound that is dangerously loud to subjects within a {{convert|2|m|ft|spell=in|adj=on|0}} radius, and numerous vuvuzelas are typically blown together for the duration of a match, it may put spectators at a significant risk of hearing loss.<ref name=\"Journal2\" /> Hearing loss experts at the U.S. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) recommend that exposure at the 113&nbsp;dB(A) level not exceed 45 seconds per day.<ref name=NIOSHvuvuzela>{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2010/06/17/vuvuzelas/ |title=CDC/NIOSH Science Blog \u2013 Vuvuzelas: What's the Buzz? June 2010|work=NIOSH|publisher=cdc.com/niosh|date=June 2010}}</ref> A newer model has a modified mouthpiece that reduces the volume by 20&nbsp;dB.<ref name=Sport24>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/New-vuvuzelas-turn-down-volume-20100614|title=New vuvuzelas turn down volume|work=Sport24|publisher=24.com|access-date=June 14, 2010|date=June 14, 2010|location=South Africa|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222134753/http://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/WorldCup/NationalNews/New-vuvuzelas-turn-down-volume-20100614|archivedate=February 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Noise levels and bans===\nConcerns about the constant intensities produced by the vuvuzelas during the 2010 FIFA World Cup matches were raised independently by representatives of international football teams, spectators and sports commentators. The noise levels that were demonstrated during the 2010 FIFA World Cup prompted various sporting organisations to ban the vuvuzela at future events and venues, even including future World Cups:\n\n* [[Wembley Stadium]] (as part of an overall ban of noisemakers)<ref name=\"WembleynBan\">{{Cite web |title=Rules & Regulations |work=Wembley Stadium |url=http://www.wembleystadium.com/TheStadium/StadiumGuide/RulesnRegulations|access-date=June 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/06/wooomp-fifa-bans-vuvuzelas-from-brazilian-world-cup/372195/|title=Wooomp: FIFA Bans Vuvuzelas from Brazilian World Cup|first=Connor|last=Simpson|date=June 4, 2014|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/2018-world-cup/88426/2018-world-cup-roll-up-for-obese-person-tickets|title=2018 World Cup: Roll up for 'obese person' tickets|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s\n* All sporting events at the [[Cardiff City Stadium|Cardiff City]], [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]], and [[Millennium Stadium]]s<ref>{{Cite news|title=Sports fans in Cardiff spared vuvuzela|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/south_east_wales/10353020.stm|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=June 18, 2010|access-date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]<ref name=\"WimbledonBan\">{{Cite news|last=Summers|first=Chris|title=Wimbledon crackdown on vuvuzelas |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tennis/wimbledon/8744027.stm|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=June 19, 2010 | date=June 16, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Lord's|Lord's Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/call-to-ban-vuvuzelas-at-edgbaston-127870|title=Call to ban vuvuzelas at Edgbaston|first=Neil|last=Elkes|date=July 9, 2010|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Vuvu gets big no-no from AFL|last=Doherty|first=Elissa|newspaper=Herald Sun|publisher=News Corporation|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/vuvu-gets-big-no-no-from-afl/story-e6frf9if-1225880671282|date=June 17, 2010|access-date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* The [[WACA Ground]] in Perth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waca.com.au/ground/at-the-ground/ground-entry-conditions|title=Ground Entry Conditions&nbsp;\u2014 WACA Western Australia Cricket Association|website=www.waca.com.au|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[The Gabba]] Cricket Ground in Brisbane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/the-ashes-2017-barmy-armys-new-chants-revealed-before-gabba-test/news-story/217258319be9b13bc92cd43d70ef06aa|title=Chant like England's Barmy Army|date=November 23, 2017|website=www.couriermail.com.au}}</ref>\n* The [[Sydney Cricket Ground]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketnsw.com.au/news/attending-the-odi-between-australia-and-india-at-the-scg/2012-02-24|title=Attending the ODI between Australia and India at the SCG|publisher=|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* The now defunct [[Champions League Twenty20]] cricket tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/sep/08/county-cricket-live|title=County cricket&nbsp;\u2014 as it happened!&nbsp;\u2014 Andy Wilson, Rob Smyth and Vic Marks|first1=Vic|last1=Marks|first2=Andy|last2=Wilson|first3=Rob|last3=Smyth|date=September 8, 2010|website=the Guardian|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Yankee Stadium]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Vuvuzelas BANNED From Yankee Stadium |work=The Huffington Post|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/06/17/vuvuzelas-banned-from-yan_n_616282.html|date=June 17, 2010|access-date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Fuji Rock Festival]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fujirockfestival.com/news/?id=969|title=\u30d6\u30d6\u30bc\u30e9\u306e\u6301\u3061\u8fbc\u307f\u53ca\u3073\u4f7f\u7528\u7981\u6b62\u306e\u304a\u9858\u3044|work=FujiRockFestival.com|publisher=SMASH Corporation|date=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n* The [[Southeastern Conference]] of US college sports<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/sec-leave-your-vuvuzelas-557799.html|author=Kristi E. Swartz|title=SEC: leave your vuvuzelas at home|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=2010-07-05}}</ref>\n* [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] events.<ref>{{Cite news|title=No Vuvuzelas allowed at UFC card|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/extra/mma/news/story?id=5343197|publisher=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=June 30, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] events<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0618/1224272793785.html |title=GAA bans vuvuzelas before they blow away the Croke Park atmosphere \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Fri, Jun 18, 2010 |work=The Irish Times |date=June 18, 2010 |access-date=2010-09-14}}</ref>\n* [[Little League World Series]] (from 2010 onward)\n* [[Providence Park]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pgepark.com/guest-guide |title=Guest Guide |publisher=Portland Timbers |access-date=2011-03-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110127134957/http://www.pgepark.com/guest-guide |archive-date=January 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[UEFA]], including all [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]], and [[European Championship]] matches<ref>[http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/5518726/uefa-bans-vuvuzelas-euro-2012-champions-league UEFA Enacts Vuvuzelas Ban], ''ESPN.com'', September 1, 2010</ref>\n* [[Rugby World Cup]] (starting in [[2011 Rugby World Cup|2011]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sarugby.com/news/News/article/sid=13830.html|title=No vuvuzelas at RWC 2011|work=SARugby.com|publisher=SARugby.com|date=June 29, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703061050/http://www.sarugby.com/news/News/article/sid%3D13830.html|archivedate=July 3, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Kontinental Hockey League]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khl.ru/news/2010/7/23/27717.html |script-title=ru:\u041a\u0425\u041b \u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0443\u0432\u0443\u0437\u0435\u043b |date=July 23, 2010 |publisher=[[Kontinental Hockey League]] |access-date=July 23, 2010 |language=Russian}}</ref>\n* [[2010 FIBA World Championship]] and other basketball tournaments from then on<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportas.delfi.lt/eurobasket2003/pasaulio-krepsinio-cempionate-vuvuzelu-negirdesime.d?id=35095573 |title=Pasaulio krep\u0161inio \u010dempionate vuvuzel\u0173 negird\u0117sime \u2013 DELFI \u017dinios |publisher=Sportas.delfi.lt |access-date=2010-09-14}}</ref>\n* [[National Football League]] (as part of an overall ban of noisemakers)\n* [[Evolution Championship Series|The Evolution Championship Series]] for [[Fighting game|fighting]] [[Esports|games]].\n* [[Vermont Principals' Association]] [[Amateur sports#High school sports|High school sports]]\n*\u00d6FB Bundesliga\n*Bundesliga (in some stadiums)\n\n[[File:Sneijder Heitinga.jpg|thumb|left|[[Wesley Sneijder]] blowing on a vuvuzela]]\nSome shopping centres in South Africa banned the use of vuvuzelas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ewn.co.za/articleprog.aspx?id=41683|title=No vuvuzelas inside Sandton City|work=Eyewitness News|publisher=Primedia Broadcasting|last=Child|first=Katharine|date=June 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006054626/http://www.ewn.co.za/articleprog.aspx?id=41683|archivedate=October 6, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=vn20100616043817493C787065|title=Shopping mall silences vuvuzela|date=June 16, 2010|work=IOL|last=Dardagan|first=Colleen|agency=South African Press Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/sport/soccer/article.aspx?id=410355|title=Vuvuzelas get red card in malls|publisher=Avusa Media Limited|work=Daily Dispatch Online|first=Msindisi|last=Fengu|date=June 18, 2010}}</ref> They were also banned at the 2010 [[Baltimore]] [[anime convention]] [[Otakon]].<ref name=\"Otakon\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.otakon.com/news_article.asp?id=539|title=Vuvuzela ban in effect|first=Arruda|last=Lou|date=July 11, 2010|work=Otakon.com}}</ref>  The convention committee declared that any attendee carrying a vuvuzela could have it confiscated from them, and that anyone blowing one could face expulsion from the event.<ref name=\"Otakon\" /><ref name=\"ANNOta\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2010-07-14/no-vuvuzelas-at-otakon|title=No Vuvuzelas at Otakon|date=July 14, 2010|work=Anime News Network}}</ref>\n\nAnother such action was taken in response to the prevalence of the vuvuzelas at the 2010 [[Anime Expo]] based in Los Angeles, attended by representatives of Otakon who felt the disruption led to discomfort for some of the attendees of Anime Expo which they wished to avoid at the later Baltimore event.<ref name=\"ANNOta\" />\n\nNine English [[Premier League]] clubs have banned the device. Five clubs ([[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/vuvuzelas-not-welcome- |title=Vuvuzelas not welcome at Emirates Stadium! |publisher=Arsenal.com |date=July 20, 2010 |access-date=2010-09-14}}</ref> [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]) have banned them due to health and safety reasons while [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] have barred them because of policy against musical instruments. [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] banned vuvuzelas from [[Old Trafford]] on August 13, 2010. However, two clubs ([[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]) have allowed them. {{citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nThe organisers of the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympic Games]] placed a ban on vuvuzelas at the sporting event.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/no-frisbees-picnic-hampers-or-vuvuzelas-items-banned-from-the-london-2012-olympics-7936428.html |title= No frisbees, picnic hampers or vuvuzelas: items banned from the London 2012 Olympics |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= July 12, 2012 |publisher=BBC News |access-date= August 30, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Usage in protests==\nOn July 13, 2010, protesters with vuvuzelas converged on [[BP]]'s London headquarters to protest the company's handling of the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]].<ref>{{Cite news | author = CNN Wire Staff | title = Vuvuzela protest planned at BP HQ | work = CNN.com Breaking News | publisher = CNN | date = July 13, 2010 | url = http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/07/13/uk.bp.vuvuzela.protest/}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Wisconsin]], anti-[[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], pro-union [[2011 Wisconsin protests|2011 Wisconsin protesters]] have made use of vuvuzelas. A Madison DJ, Nick Nice, [http://www.thedailypage.com/isthmus/article.php?article=33472 ordered 200] and distributed them to his fellow protesters. The Madison police even issued permits for use of the vuvuzelas ''inside'' the capitol.{{Citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\nIn March 2012, German protesters used vuvuzelas during the official traditional torchlight ceremony, the [[Gro\u00dfer Zapfenstreich]], which bid farewell to [[President of Germany]] [[Christian Wulff]]. Wulff had resigned earlier over corruption allegations, yet he still received the honor of the military ceremony, which left Germany divided. [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0,1518,820452,00.html Tr\u00f6ten beim Zapfenstreich: Bellevue beschwert sich \u00fcber Vuvuzela-Demo]\n\n== Usage in music ==\nUsage of vuvuzela in art music is limited. One of the few compositions made for it is a baroque-style [[double concerto]] in C major for vuvuzela, [[organ (music)|organ]] (or [[harpsichord]]) and string orchestra, written by [[Timo Kiiskinen]], Professor of Church Music in [[Sibelius Academy]], [[Helsinki]]; organ version of this concerto was premiered on 21 October 2010 at the Organ Hall of Sibelius Academy, and harpsichord version on 19 December 2010 at Pro Puu gallery in Lahti.<ref>https://cris.uniarts.fi/crisyp/disp/_/fi/cr_redir_all/fet/fet/sea?direction=2&id=3477372 (in Finnish)</ref><ref>\"Barokkiyhtyeen joulukonsertissa soi vuvuzela\" [http://www.ess.fi/uutiset/kulttuurijaviihde/2010/12/16/barokkiyhtyeen-joulukonsertissa-soi-vuvuzela]. ''Etel\u00e4-Suomen sanomat'' 16.12.2010 (in Finnish)</ref>\n\nAlternative rock band Catzo Music All-Stars used two vuvuzelas as the basis of its 2010 song \"Larissa Riquelme (reprise)\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Makarapa]]&nbsp;\u2014 hand-made hats worn by spectators to show their team support\n* [[Air horn#Portable or personal air horns|Portable or personal air horns]]&nbsp;\u2014 produce sounds similar to the vuvuzela\n* [[Ratchet (instrument)|Football rattle]]&nbsp;\u2014 a percussion instrument which produces a clicking and rattling noise\n* [[Thundersticks]]&nbsp;\u2014 narrow plastic balloons used as promotional noise makers\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Vuvuzelas}}\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/africa/10312794.stm 10 Things about the Vuvuzela by the BBC]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7X3fkvhd-5g Promotional film for World Cup Mexico 86 \u2013 Mexican plastic trumpets are shown] \u2013 YouTube\n* [http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/64381,in-pictures,news-in-pictures,vuvuzela-day-in-pictures-bafana-world-cup-football-south-africa Vuvuzela Day] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[The First Post]]''\n* {{cite web|last=Moriarty|first=Philip|title=Vuvuzela|url=http://www.sixtysymbols.com/videos/vuvuzela.htm|work=Sixty Symbols|publisher=[[Brady Haran]] for the [[University of Nottingham]]|year=2010}}\n\n{{2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Fanatism in Association football}}\n{{Natural horns and trumpets}}\n\n[[Category:Association football culture]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup controversies]]\n[[Category:Brass instruments]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:Zulu words and phrases]]\n[[Category:South African English]]\n[[Category:Natural horns and trumpets]]\n[[Category:1965 musical instruments]]\n[[Category:2010 controversies]]\n[[Category:South African inventions]]\n", "name_user": "OnYourLeftz", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOrigin:the proper term)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vuvuzela"}
