 level of [[Polish Volleyball League]]<ref>[http://www.pzps.pl/PLPS-podjela-decyzje-o-powiekszeniu-PlusLigi.html ''PLPS podj\u0119\u0142a decyzj\u0119 o powi\u0119kszeniu PlusLigi''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205071822/http://www.pzps.pl/PLPS-podjela-decyzje-o-powiekszeniu-PlusLigi.html |date=2014-12-05 }} \u2013 pzps.pl \u2013 18-06-2013</ref>. Since 2018 club has been playing in 1st Polish Volleyball League.\n\n==Achievements==\n* [[PlusLiga|Polish Championship]]\n*: [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 1993\n* [[Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]]\n*: [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 1994\n\n==Coaches==\n{|\n|-\n| '''2012\u20132014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Janusz Bu\u0142kowski\n|- \n| '''2014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Wiktor Krebok\n|-\n| '''2014\u20132015''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Piotr Gruszka]]\n|-\n| '''2015\u20132016''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Krzysztof Stelmach]]\n|-\n| '''2016''' || {{flagicon|SVK}} Miroslav Palgut\n|-\n| '''2016\u20132017''' || {{flagicon|SVK}} Rastislav Chud\u00edk\n|-\n| '''2017\u20132019''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Pawe\u0142 Gradowski\n|-\n| '''2019\u2013present''' || {{flagicon|NED}} [[Harry Brokking]]\n|}\n\n==Team==\n{{main|BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a squads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Volleyball in Poland]]\n* [[Sports in Poland]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:BPTS Siatkarz Bielsko-Biala}}\n[[Category:Polish volleyball clubs]]\n[[Category:Sport in Silesian Voivodeship]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBTS_Bielsko-Bia%C5%82a"}
{"title_page": "Woodville Oval", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Maughan Thiem Hyundai Oval\n| nickname          = Pecker Park<br>Warrior Park<br>Eagles Nest<br>Oval Ave\n| image             = [[File:Woodvilleoval.jpg|thumb|]]\n| image_caption     = Woodville Oval in 2004\n| location          = Oval Avenue, [[Woodville, South Australia|Woodville]], [[South Australia]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|34|53|17|S|138|32|18|E|display=it}}\n| broke_ground      = \n| opened            = \n| owner             = [[City of Charles Sturt]]\n| operator          = [[Woodville-West Torrens Football Club]]\n| surface           = Grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = \n| former_names      = Woodville Oval<br>Unleash Solar Oval\n| tenants           = [[Woodville-West Torrens Football Club]] ([[SANFL]]) (1992-present)<br>[[Woodville Football Club]] (SANFL) (1941-1990)<br>[[Woodville Cricket Club]]\n| seating_capacity  = 15,000\n| record_attendance = 11,026 \u2013 Woodville vs [[Port Adelaide Magpies|Port Adelaide]], 9 August 1986\n| dimensions        = '''Football''': 175m x 110m\n|}}\n\n'''Woodville Oval''' (currently '''Maughan Thiem Hyundai Oval''' and formerly ''Unleash Solar Oval'') is primarily an [[Australian rules football]] and [[cricket]] oval found on Oval Avenue in the western [[Adelaide]] suburb of [[Woodville, South Australia|Woodville]] in [[South Australia]]. It is the home ground of [[South Australian National Football League]] (SANFL) club the [[Woodville-West Torrens Eagles]], and the former home (1941\u201390) of the [[Woodville Football Club]], with the former's clubrooms and administrations offices now housing The Eagles. The oval is also the home of the [[Woodville Cricket Club]] who play in the [[South Australian Grade Cricket League]].\n\n==The Oval==\nWoodville Oval has a capacity of around 15,000 people, with seating for up to 2,000 in two covered stands located on the western side of the ground, with the players changerooms located under the [[Barry Jarman]] Stand on the centre wing. Most of the spectator areas around the ground are grass banks, with the exception of the outer (eastern) wing which is six rows of concrete terracing. The playing surface of the oval is 175m x 110m making it the second longest currently in use in the SANFL behind [[Elizabeth Oval]] (178m),{{cn|date=August 2018}} though if measured from fence to fence, Woodville Oval is 203m long, some 15 metres longer than Elizabeth.{{cn|date=August 2018}} The main scoreboard at the oval is located in the north-eastern corner of the ground adjacent to the Woodville-West Torrens clubrooms which are located behind the northern goals.\n\nThe ground record attendance was set on 9 August 1986 when 11,026 saw Woodville, led by Captain-coach and club legend [[Malcolm Blight]], and on their way to a rare SANFL finals appearance, defeat their hated western suburbs 'big brother' [[Port Adelaide Magpies|Port Adelaide]] 14.11 (95) to 13.11 (89) in their Round 18 match.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qKo6b-I9nP0 Woodville vs Port Adelaide 1986]</ref>\n\nAdjoining the Oval directly to the north is the Woodville Lawn Bowling Club, the Woodville Croquet Club and the Woodville Glengarry Tennis Club, with both lawn and hardcourts it is one of the largest multi surface tennis clubs in the Adelaide.\n\nOn-site car parking is available for Eagles members, located near the Eagles club rooms in the north-west of the facility while limited on-street parking is available for the general public during Eagles SANFL games at the ground.\n\nWoodville Oval is located approximately 600 metres from one of Adelaide's major public hospitals, the [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Adelaide|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Austadiums|210}}\n\n{{SANFL grounds|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football grounds]]\n\n\n{{Australia-sports-venue-stub}}\n{{AFL-stub}}\n{{SouthAustralia-struct-stub}}\n\n{{PD-self\n|name       = <!-- Your name, assuming you are the copyright holder -->\n|date       = August 2018\n|no Commons = <!-- set to \"yes\" if the image can't be used on Commons -->\n}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Maughan Thiem Hyundai Oval\n| nickname          = Pecker Park<br>Warrior Park<br>Eagles Nest<br>Oval Ave\n| image             =\n| image_caption     = Woodville Oval in 2004\n| location          = Oval Avenue, [[Woodville, South Australia|Woodville]], [[South Australia]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|34|53|17|S|138|32|18|E|display=it}}\n| broke_ground      = \n| opened            = \n| owner             = [[City of Charles Sturt]]\n| operator          = [[Woodville-West Torrens Football Club]]\n| surface           = Grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = \n| former_names      = Woodville Oval<br>Unleash Solar Oval\n| tenants           = [[Woodville-West Torrens Football Club]] ([[SANFL]]) (1992-present)<br>[[Woodville Football Club]] (SANFL) (1941-1990)<br>[[Woodville Cricket Club]]\n| seating_capacity  = 15,000\n| record_attendance = 11,026 \u2013 Woodville vs [[Port Adelaide Magpies|Port Adelaide]], 9 August 1986\n| dimensions        = '''Football''': 175m x 110m\n|}}\n\n'''Woodville Oval''' (currently '''Maughan Thiem Hyundai Oval''' and formerly ''Unleash Solar Oval'') is primarily an [[Australian rules football]] and [[cricket]] oval found on Oval Avenue in the western [[Adelaide]] suburb of [[Woodville, South Australia|Woodville]] in [[South Australia]]. It is the home ground of [[South Australian National Football League]] (SANFL) club the [[Woodville-West Torrens Eagles]], and the former home (1941\u201390) of the [[Woodville Football Club]], with the former's clubrooms and administrations offices now housing The Eagles. The oval is also the home of the [[Woodville Cricket Club]] who play in the [[South Australian Grade Cricket League]].\n\n==The Oval==\nWoodville Oval has a capacity of around 15,000 people, with seating for up to 2,000 in two covered stands located on the western side of the ground, with the players changerooms located under the [[Barry Jarman]] Stand on the centre wing. Most of the spectator areas around the ground are grass banks, with the exception of the outer (eastern) wing which is six rows of concrete terracing. The playing surface of the oval is 175m x 110m making it the second longest currently in use in the SANFL behind [[Elizabeth Oval]] (178m),{{cn|date=August 2018}} though if measured from fence to fence, Woodville Oval is 203m long, some 15 metres longer than Elizabeth.{{cn|date=August 2018}} The main scoreboard at the oval is located in the north-eastern corner of the ground adjacent to the Woodville-West Torrens clubrooms which are located behind the northern goals.\n\nThe ground record attendance was set on 9 August 1986 when 11,026 saw Woodville, led by Captain-coach and club legend [[Malcolm Blight]], and on their way to a rare SANFL finals appearance, defeat their hated western suburbs 'big brother' [[Port Adelaide Magpies|Port Adelaide]] 14.11 (95) to 13.11 (89) in their Round 18 match.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qKo6b-I9nP0 Woodville vs Port Adelaide 1986]</ref>\n\nAdjoining the Oval directly to the north is the Woodville Lawn Bowling Club, the Woodville Croquet Club and the Woodville Glengarry Tennis Club, with both lawn and hardcourts it is one of the largest multi surface tennis clubs in the Adelaide.\n\nOn-site car parking is available for Eagles members, located near the Eagles club rooms in the north-west of the facility while limited on-street parking is available for the general public during Eagles SANFL games at the ground.\n\nWoodville Oval is located approximately 600 metres from one of Adelaide's major public hospitals, the [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Adelaide|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Austadiums|210}}\n\n{{SANFL grounds|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues in Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football grounds]]\n\n\n{{Australia-sports-venue-stub}}\n{{AFL-stub}}\n{{SouthAustralia-struct-stub}}\n\n{{PD-self\n|name       = <!-- Your name, assuming you are the copyright holder -->\n|date       = August 2018\n|no Commons = <!-- set to \"yes\" if the image can't be used on Commons -->\n}}\n", "name_user": "CharVixen", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodville_Oval"}
